Global Empirical Analysis: Relationship between Income & Life Expectancy

Deerasinghe T.

20/10/2024



Research Outline

Background

Life expectancy is the average number of years people live from birth. Life expectancy is a crucial indicator for evaluating public health and standard of living. High life expectancy is frequently associated with access to quality healthcare, clean water, nutritious food, and safe living conditions. In contrast, low life expectancy often correlates with limited access to these basic necessities. Therefore, it is essential to comprehend the impact of income on life expectancy to develop effective policies that reduce health disparities and improve population health.

Research Question

Is income a significant factor for life expectancy?

Research Objective

This research investigate the association between income and life expectancy, considering potential other predictors such as urbanisation, unemployment, health expenditure and region. The objective is to identify the effect of income and its interplay with other factors on life expectancy.

Research Hypothesis

The primary hypothesis of this research is that individual income has a significant impact on life expectancy while controlling for other factors.


Dataset & Variables

Dataset

The dataset was created from World Bank Development Indicators, with values from 2021 used to create the dataset. The reason for using data from 2021 is that health expenditure data was only published up to that year.

Variables Used

Variable Variable_Name Description
Life Expectancy at birth,total (years) life_expectancy Life expectancy at birth indicates the number of years a newborn infant would live if prevailing patterns of mortality at the time of its birth were to stay the same throughout its life.
Gross national income per capita (Atlas moethod) GNIpc GNI is the sum of value added by all resident producers plus any product taxes (less subsidies) not included in the valuation of output plus net receipts of primary income (compensation of employees and property income) from abroad.
Urban population (% of total population) urbanisation Urban population refers to people living in urban areas as defined by national statistical offices.
Unemployment, total (% of total labor force) (modeled ILO estimate) unemployment Unemployment refers to the share of the labor force that is without work but available for and seeking employment.
Current health expenditure per capita (current US$) healthexpenditure_pc Current expenditures on health per capita in current US dollars. Estimates of current health expenditures include healthcare goods and services consumed during each year.

Why these variables used for analysis?

GNI per capita, urbanization, unemployment, and health expenditure per capita are socio-economic factors that can provide valuable insights into factors that affect life expectancy. Higher GNI per capita is typically associated with better access to healthcare, healthier lifestyles, and overall better living conditions (Aimbetova, 2022), all of which can lead to increased life expectancy. Urbanization is also an important factor to consider, as it can affect access to healthcare and living conditions (Godfrey & Julien, 2005). Unemployment, on the other hand, can be a negative factor for life expectancy. Being unemployed can lead to stress, reduced income, and fewer opportunities to access healthcare (Wilson & Walker, 1993). Health expenditure is often considered a key indicator of the quality and accessibility of healthcare (Onofrei et al., 2021). Higher health expenditure per capita may lead to improved access to healthcare, better disease prevention and treatment, and ultimately, increased life expectancy.


Data Cleaning

  • Countries where life expectancy values is missing were removed and other variables were imputed using tree based imputation method using recipe functions in R.

  • According to the World Bank regions South Asia region and North America regions have only few countries (8 and 3 respectively). This data imbalance might be problematic for model building process. Therefore based on the geographical location regions South Asia was merged together with East Asia & Pacific; and North America was merged together with Europe & Central Asia.

Exploratory Data Analysis

Distribution of Life Expectancy


Skewness = -0.3366

  • Distribution of the life expectancy shows a slight symmetrical distribution and deviates from the normal distribution. The skewness value of -0.3366 for the life_expectancy variable indicates a slight left skew in the distribution of the data. This negative skewness suggests that the left tail of the distribution is longer or more pronounced than the right tail, implying that there are a few observations with lower life expectancy that are pulling the average down. However, the value is relatively close to zero, indicating that the skewness is not very pronounced and that the distribution is mostly symmetric. And also, there are multiple peaks (multi-model distribution) in the distribution showing there should be an effect of a categorical variable which affects the distribution of life_expectancy .

Boxplots of Life Expectancy in different Regions

  • life_expectancy of the region Sub-Saharan Africa is significantly lower that the other regions and life_expectancy is approximately equal in all the other regions.

Correlation Matrix

  • According to the correlation matrix variables GNIpc, healthexpenditure_pc, urbanisation show positive correlations with life_expectancy implying that when those variables increase life_expectancy also should increase. However variable unemployment show negative correlations with life_expectancy.

  • When regions taken into consideration correlation of and GNIpc and healthexpenditure_pc with life_expectancy is highest in South Asia, East Asia and Pacific region. Correlation between life_expectancy and urban_population highest in Middle East & North Africa region and also Middle East & North Africa has the highest magnitude of correlation between life_expectancy and unemployment. This implies that relationship between explanatory variables and the response variable could be different from region to region.

  • There is a almost perfect linear positive correlation between the explanatory variables GNIpc and healthexpenditure_pc, which implies that countries with higher GNIpc tends to spends more on health_expenditure_pc as well.This may be an issue in the OLS regression because correlation between explanatory variables causes multicolinearity. Therefore, variables healthexpenditure_pc should be dropped from OLS modeling since our main variable of interest is GNIpc .


Analysis Results

Model level statistics

r.squared adj.r.squared sigma statistic p.value df
0.7370908 0.7254429 4.032968 63.28113 0 7

The regression analysis yields an R-squared value of approximately 0.7371, indicating that about 73.71% of the variability in life expectancy can be explained by the model’s predictors. This suggests that the model fits the data well and that the predictors have a substantial effect on life expectancy. The standard error of the regression (sigma) is approximately 4.03, indicating that the predicted life expectancy values are, on average, about 4.03 units away from the actual observed values. The F-statistic is 63.28113, which signifies that the overall model is statistically significant, as it is considerably greater than 1, implying that at least one of the predictors in the model has a meaningful relationship with life expectancy. The associated p-value of 0 provides strong evidence against the null hypothesis, suggesting that the model offers a significantly better fit to the data than a model with no predictors. Overall, these results demonstrate the effectiveness of the model in explaining the variations in life expectancy based on predictors GNI per capita, urban population, region and unemployment.

Model Equation

\[ \hat{Y} = 68.5911 + 0.0001 \times \text{GNIpc} + 0.0580 \times \text{urbanisation } + 0.0155 \times \text{unemployment} \] \[ - 0.8716 \times \text{region LAC} - 0.5980 \times \text{region MNA} \] \[ - 0.4770 \times \text{region SA and EAP} - 9.7238 \times \text{region SSA} \]

Where:

  • \(\hat{Y}\) is the predicted life expectancy.
  • GNIpc is the Gross National Income per Capita.
  • urbanisation Urban population (% of total population).
  • unemployment is Unemployment, total (% of total labor force).

Region Dummy Variables

The region dummy variables are encoded as follows:

  • regionLAC = 1 if the region is Latin America & Caribbean; 0 otherwise.
  • regionMNA = 1 if the region is Middle East & North Africa; 0 otherwise.
  • regionSA_EAP = 1 if the region is South Asia, East Asia & Pacific; 0 otherwise.
  • regionSSA = 1 if the region is Sub-Saharan Africa; 0 otherwise.

The reference region is EAC & NAR (Europe & Central Asia & North America). Research selected EAC & NAR region because this region has the highest life expectancy among all regions, therefore is a good candidate for reference.


Model Interpretation

The model explores how life expectancy is influenced by GNI per capita, urban population, unemployment, and regional differences. Using EAC & NAR (Europe & Central Asia and North America) as the reference region, the intercept of 68.59 represents the estimated life expectancy in this region when all other predictors are at zero. GNI per capita has a significant positive effect (p-value = 0.0000), suggesting that higher GNI per capita is associated with increased life expectancy, though the effect size is small at 0.0001 per unit increase. Urban population also has a positive and significant effect (0.058, p-value = 0.0004), indicating that for every 1 unit increase in urban population, life expectancy increases by 0.058 years. Unemployment, however, is not statistically significant (p-value = 0.8112), implying it has no meaningful impact on life expectancy in this model.

Regarding regional differences, LAC (Latin America & Caribbean) has a negative coefficient (-0.8716) but is not statistically significant (p-value = 0.2840), suggesting no meaningful difference in life expectancy compared to EAC & NAR. Similarly, MNA (Middle East & North Africa, -0.5980, p-value = 0.5100) and SA & EAP (South Asia & East Asia & Pacific, -0.4770, p-value = 0.5998) show no significant differences from the reference region. However, SSA (Sub-Saharan Africa) has a large and significant negative effect (-9.7238, p-value = 0.0000), indicating that life expectancy in SSA is approximately 9.72 years lower than in EAC & NAR, underscoring the significant disparity in health outcomes between these regions.

Final Model Selection

In the model-building process, health expenditure was initially excluded from the OLS model due to multicollinearity. To improve predictive accuracy, log transformations were applied to variables, reducing skewness and improving performance without introducing bias. Regularization technique, Elastic Net, which combines ridge and lasso methods, were employed to address multicollinearity and reduce variance, though they added some bias. As a result, ridge and lasso were not considered separately. This regularized regression method is more complex and harder to interpret than OLS models. The trade-off between bias and variance was considered, with Elastic Net providing a more stable solution. OLS assumptions, including normality, homoscedasticity, and independence of errors and multicolinearity between predictors were also carefully examined to ensure model validity. Model selection was based on R-squared, RMSE, and MAPE, providing a balanced view of fit, prediction error, and accuracy.


Conclusion

Salient Findings

  1. The research found out that GNI per capita has a significant positive effect, suggesting that higher GNI per capita is associated with increased life expectancy, though the effect size is small. GNI per capita and its significant effect on life expectancy aligns with the findings of Mondal and Shitan (2013) and Chetty et al. (2016). Governments should develop effective policies that reduce health disparities and improve population health for low income individuals and populations.

  2. Urban population also has a positive significant effect, indicating that for every 1 unit increase in urban population, life expectancy increases by 0.058 years. The significant impact of Urbanization on life expectancy aligns with the findings of Ahmad et al. (2023). Governments should develop effective policies for people in rural areas that reduce health disparities and improve population health.

  3. However, unemployment is has no significant which implies that it has no meaningful influence on life expectancy.

  4. All regions except SSA (Sub-Saharan Africa), show no significant effect on life expectancy from the reference region EAC & NAR (Europe & Central Asia & North America). However, SSA (Sub-Saharan Africa) has a large 9.72 years lower life expectancy than in EAC & NAR; and significant negative effect on life expectancy indicating the significant disparity in health outcomes between these regions.

Limitations

  1. Data Limitations

    Research had to exclude variables such as poverty and income inequality due to lack of data availability. The lack of individual-level data on socioeconomic factors, the true impact of income on life expectancy was the other data limitation. The reliance on country-based measures of income in the analysis further highlights the limitations of the data.

  2. Robustness of the Model

    Final model had to exclude variable health expenditure per capita data due to mutlicolinearity with GNI per capita. Also the final model has serial correlation, also known as autocorrelation, occurs when the regression residuals are correlated with each other. However, autocorrelation was corrected during the modeling process.

Regularized Regression

  • Among the predictors, healthexpenditure_pc and GNIpcwere correlated, leading to multicollinearity in the OLS models.While lasso performs feature selection by shrinking some coefficients to zero, it can arbitrarily eliminate one correlated feature and keep the other. Ridge regression, on the other hand, tends to shrink coefficients equally without selecting features. The elastic net combines the strengths of both: it provides the systematic handling of correlated features from ridge regression while retaining the feature selection ability of lasso. This makes elastic net more effective than either lasso or ridge when dealing with multicollinearity in OLS models. Therefore under net elastic regression all the predictors considered initially were included including both healthexpenditure_pc and GNIpc.

  • In the elastic net method, all predictor variables were standardized to have a mean of 0 and a unit variance. Additionally, numeric predictor columns with a single value (i.e., zero variance) were identified and excluded from further calculations, as they do not contribute any meaningful information to the model.

  • To identify the optimal Ridge penalty (α) and Lasso penalty (λ), a 10-fold cross-validation was performed using the glmnet::cv.glmnet() function. The best combination of α and λ was determined by selecting the values that minimized the Root Mean Square Error (RMSE).

# Convert the categorical variable 'region' into dummy variables and remove the intercept (-1)
X <- model.matrix(life_expectancy ~ region + GNIpc + urbanisation + healthexpenditure_pc + unemployment - 1, 
                  data = train_data)

# Response variable
Y <- train_data$life_expectancy

set.seed(123)  # Ensures the training/testing split and cross-validation are reproducible
# Fit the Elastic Net model with cross-validation
cv_glmnet <- train(
  x = X,                   # Predictor matrix (now with dummy variables)
  y = Y,                   # Response variable
  method = "glmnet",        # Elastic Net model
  preProc = c("zv", "center", "scale"),  # Preprocessing: remove zero variance, center, and scale
  trControl = trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10),  # 10-fold cross-validation
  tuneLength = 10          # Test 10 different combinations of alpha and lambda
)
# Ensure that lambda is numeric in the plot
ggplot(cv_glmnet$results, aes(x = as.numeric(lambda), y = RMSE, color = as.factor(alpha))) + 
  geom_point() + 
  scale_x_log10() + 
  labs(title = "Cross-validated RMSE for Elastic Net",
       x = "Lambda (Log Scale)", y = "RMSE") + 
  theme_minimal()

# View the results for the best alpha and lambda combination

filtered_results <- cv_glmnet$results %>%
  filter(alpha == cv_glmnet$bestTune$alpha, lambda == cv_glmnet$bestTune$lambda)

 filtered_results

Model Validation

  • Among the OLS models model with normalized variables with log transformation performs better but there is no significance difference between the performance compared to the other model. Therefore to select the better model for making inferences model validation was carried out using Shapiro-Wilk test for Normality, Breusch-Pagan test for heteroskadasticity, Breusch-Godfrey test for serial correlation. And also, variance inflation factors were calculated to check for multicollinearity.

  • Both models do not violate the normality of the error term or the assumption of no multicollinearity. However, the OLS model violates the assumption of no serial correlation in the error terms, while the LOG model does not meet the homoscedasticity assumption at the 0.05 level of significance. Notably, the OLS model does not violate any assumptions at the 0.01 level of significance. Consequently, the OLS model is utilized for making inferences, and Newey-West standard errors were applied to correct for the serial correlation violation prior to making inferences.
